<hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px;"><small><br>
</small><small><span style="font-weight: bold; font-family: arial;">Command
Line Interface (CLI)</span></small><small><span
 style="font-family: arial;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br>
<span style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Updated (June 12, 2008):</span>&nbsp;
Uses a more unix-like command line interface; allows reading of files
from any directory<br>
<br>
</span></span></small><small><span
 style="font-weight: bold; font-family: arial;">Instructions</span><span
 style="font-family: arial;">: <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Download <a href="CRT1.2-CLI.jar.zip">CRT1.2-CLI.jar.zip</a>
</span></small><small><span style="font-family: arial;">and unzip the
file to a folder.&nbsp; (The extracted file should be
named CRT1.2-CLI.jar)</span></small><br>
<small><span style="font-family: arial;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the
command line type:&nbsp; <span
 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;">java -cp CRT1.2-CLI.jar
crt [options] inputFile [outputFile]</span></span></small><br>
<small><span style="font-family: arial;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></small><small><span
 style="font-family: arial;"></span></small><br>
<small><span style="font-family: arial;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Please,
click <a href="cli.html">here</a> for a more detailed description of
the command line interface.<br>
